			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I started playing EQ in february 2000, started working on this character in may 2000.
<br />

<br />
My first character was a magician. I had a group of ~10 regular friends to play with, including an enchanter. My favorite part of EQ was dungeon crawling. There's nothing like the feel these places had - Solusek A&B, Splitpaw, Kedge Keep, Guk, Cazic Thule, etc... Unfortunately when our enchanter wasn't on, we were pretty much screwed. The absence of crowd control in the pre pacify EQ was very hard to handle even with good players. Not to mention the buffs were actually useful (no KEI), and slow (only 2 slowing classes back then - bards couldn't slow to a reasonable level and beastlords didn't exist). 
<br />

<br />
Anyway it was a lot of fun back then. I leveled through the dungeons, then Kunark with Karnor and Old Sebilis. Then things started to go the wrong way. First Velious, which introduced raids where we did nothing but buff. Back then with a level cap of 60 and no aas, that's pretty much all that I did (raiding I mean) except misc quests. 
<br />

<br />
Then Luclin came, with aas. I thought that would be great to be useful again in groups! Big mistake. People were level pulling everywhere, in small groups of 1-4 people, and an enchanter wasn't worth the group slot. Finding a group of level 60s (except pity groups from friends) was near impossible. There were AE groups eventually, but I never liked AE, mostly because of the disruption involved (especially the training). I quit for a few weeks. Things improved after a few months though. Dire charm, revamped CT, higher level mobs giving more xp which greatly increased the value of an enchanter - these mobs were mostly deep in dungeons and level pulling wasn't possible. Then focus items, especially affliction focus. The raiding game stayed stale by and large, but grouping was fun again. Given that I was raiding a lot back then, I switched my main to a cleric.
<br />

<br />
Then PoP came out. I played my enchanter for a few days, then realized everything was a single pull and that a shaman was so much better suited for the role, and went back to my cleric. A few weeks in the expansion, I the power of charm in PoP started to be felt more and more, for a couple of reasons:
<br />
-the level of mobs that could be charmed was comparatively much higher. Boltran at level 60 was the best charm spell with a cap of 53, which was close to useless in all pre PoP raiding content. The new charm had a level cap of 64, meaning a huge portion of the mobs were charmable.
<br />
-Most PoP mobs do not summon. This was such a huge difference from the end of the luclin days. Everything that was good xp at level 60 (55+ mobs) summoned. Soloing was impossible or impractical. Suddenly, anyone with a charm spell and root or any caster with snare could solo for godly xp. 
<br />
-Crowd control not needed. With the pacify line now working, along with the natural ease of single pulling in PoP, mezzing was simply redundant. Given that you did not take an enchanter for CC anymore, there was mana and time available for the now incredibly more powerful ability to charm.
<br />

<br />
So we had a new situation where crowd control was obsolete, but charming useful. And enchanters were useful in raids too! - after a lull of 2 years of near uselessness through 2 entire expansions. 
<br />

<br />
Too powerful maybe. The first charm nerf significantly reduced the usefulness  of charmed pets in raids. One overlooked feature was the aggro these pets generated. Even if they were not actually tanking because others were in melee range, the aggro they generated were invariably pushing them at the top of the hate list, making the mob hit the people in melee range that was highest on the hate list - thus giving immunity to wizards and clerics. This was actually imo the main benefit charmed pets brought to raids. The DPS was still helpful for a few raids, but once in elemental and beyond it was back to buffbot except for the elemental gods events. Enchanters stayed solid in groups, with the ability to add unrivaled dps at an acceptable level of risk. 
<br />

<br />
Bring in GoD. Enchanters are overpowered in groups due to charm til KT and beyond.  Enchanters deficiencies at melee support that I noticed in PoP surface again, but are amplified by higher dps on mobs, higher resist rate, and lower hps. With the inability to slow reasonably fast without getting aggro, With in camp CC being a bad idea - CC has to be done through pulling, with lower dps than their rivals, enchanters are a distant 4th to shamans, bards and beastlords in these zones. At the same time, it's also becoming quite obvious that if CC is needed, it's better handled by bards due to the relative inability of enchanters to survive aggro on resists or accidently broken mezzes. 
<br />

<br />
Bring in OoW. Charm is nerfed in uselessness, Crowd control is still redundant, and if not, better done through pulling or handled by bards. 
<br />
Enchanters are still a distant 4th in general support behind beastlords, shamans and bards. With the slow erosion of their abilities, either discontinued or given in better versions to other classes, enchanters have no class definition anymore beyond buffs. Given that I do not expect SoE to react in a timely fashion given previous historical class imbalance situations (monks, anyone?), I cancelled my 3 accounts.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
